x4freetext: Information
about facilities, and instrumentation.
Measurement of the neutron induced fission
cross-section of Am-241 from 100 eV to 5.3 MeV
7 MB CBNM accelerator at Geel.
-For neutron energies above 4.5 MeV,pulse mode gave
deuterons 4-micro-A-average current,1.5 nsec pulse
width,2.5 MHz repetition frequency.See 1st n-source.
-From 1 to 4.5 MeV n-energies,pulsed mode with the
same characteristics as above gave protons
2nd n-source.
-From 0.153 to 1.3 MeV, dc-mode gave P with a 80 Watts
power.See 3rd n-source. While pulsed mode allowed a
neutron TOF spectra measurement.
-For neutron energies below 300 keV,pulsed mode gave
protons.See 3rd n-source.
A 5cm collimated neutron beam of the
electron LINAC of the CBNM,operated with a pulse width
of 4.4 nsec,a repetition frequency of 800 Hz and an
average beam power of 4KW at 100 MeV.
For n-energies above 4.5 MeV monoenergetic
neutrons deuterium gas was employed.
For n-energy range from 1 to 4.5 MeV
tritium loaded Ti-layers on 0.3 mm thick silver
backings were used as targets. Monoenergetic neutrons.
For n-energy range from 153 to 1300 keV.
Air-cooled targets made of LiF on 0.3 mm thick silver
backings. Monoenergetic neutrons.
For n-energies below 300 keV target was a 1 mm
thick metallic lithium disc covered by a 50 microns
thick Al-foil. Broad spectrum of neutrons was
produced.
.The neutron beam of CBNM Linac gave neutrons in the
range of energy from 1 eV to 2.5 MeV.
.Two 2.5 cm diam samples of chemically pure Am, were
used in two identical ionization chambers, back to
back with two U-235 samples.
.The relevant data are following (C means chamber No).
.Pu-239 has been identified as major contaminant with
a relative number of Pu-239 nuclei of (0.69+-.10)%.
.Two chambers were used(1 and 2),chamber1 for
monoenergetic source measurements,chamber2 for
white-source measurements.
.For measurements carried out with VdG above 300 keV,
in pulsed mode,a time correlated and a
time-uncorrelated spectrum was recorded during the
same measuring time. For those in dc-mode only
foreground spectra were registered.
.For measurements with VDG below 300 keV in pulsed
mode the time of flight spectra were recorded.
.For Linac measurements TOF spectra were recorded.
.Above 2 keV U-235 chamber part was used to determine
the energy dependence of the neutron flux. Below an
ionization chamber loaded with a sample of LiF was
used to determine the energy dep. of neutron flux.
For resonance measurement below(20 eV),U-235 was
used again.
Single layers of U-235 and Am-241 mounted back
to back in a special double-function ionization
chamber with an intrinsic suppression of alpha
background.The lower part of the chamber was used for
U-235 fission-fragment detection. The upper was used
as a parallel plate chamber for Am-241 FF detection.
A collimator was placed above the sample.
Chamber was positioned at 6 or 20 cm from the neutron
producing target for monoenergetic or white-source
measurements,respectively,at zero deg with respect to
the incident ion beam of the accelerator.
See for more details NIM.
.Neutron detector positioned at the zero deg direction,
at a distance from neutron prod.Target chosen between
2.8 and 11.3 m,according to n-energy and n-energy
spread to be measured. No other information given.
.The fission cross sections of Am-241 was obtained
according to the following expression
sig241(E) = N(U)*FA(E)*C(E)*Cg*sig235(E)
N(A)*FU(E)*Epsi*Ct*FU(E)
where - N(U),N(A) numbers of U-235 and Am-241 nuclei.
- FA(E),FU(E) numbers of detected fission
events at E-energy for Am and U,respectively.
- C(E), Ct correction factors for angular
anisotropy effects and fission layer geometry
effects.
- Cg corrects for the difference in geometry of
the two fission layers with respect to the
neutron target. It includes also the neutron
absorption by the backing material.
- Epsi,collimator efficiency.
- Sig235(E),U-235 ENDF/B-IV standard fission cs.
- C239(E),taken from Pu-239/U-235 ENDF/B-IV
fission cs.evaluation of Poenitz et al. Sup.
to NEANDC(US)-199/l,page 83.
Fission widths were calculated from fission
area using neutron widths and total widths given by
Derrien and Lucas,75Wash,vol.2,page 637.
was used for correction
.Data were corrected for time-correlated and time
uncorrelated background,for Pu-239 contamination.
For detection of fission events.
For fission width measurements.
For spectra measurement.
.Comparison with other data made,and curves given.
.This compilation includes the ratios
measured at the VDG,and presented in AKE,78,as well
as the absolute value of Am-241 fission cross-section
given in private communication(Knitter 780428) by the
author,each in different subentries.
.Data taken from AKE,78 and from private
communication

x4freetext: Due to the relative high amount of Pu-239 in
the Am-241 sample only a limited number of Am-241
resonances could be analysed.
In the energy range from 1 eV to 15 eV ten Am-241
resonances could be identified and their fission widths
were derived by area analysis.
The absolute neutron flux Was again determined from
the observed number of fission events between 7.8 eV
and 11.0 eV in the U-235 fission chamber and
normalizing to 240.0 b*eV
The fission widths were calculated from the fission
areas using the neutron widths and the total widths
given by Derrien and Lucas: Proc. of Conf. on Nuclear
Cross Sections and Technology, Washington, D.c.,
March 1975, vol. II page 637
